Today=E2=80=99s Stratechery Update interview is, from one perspective, anot=
her installment of the Stratechery Founder series; as a reminder, one of th=
e challenges in covering startups is the lack of available data. My solutio=
n is to go in the opposite direction and interview founders directly, letti=
ng them give their subjective overview of their companies, while pressing t=
hem on their business model, background, and long-term potential.

Another area of great interest to me, though, are new business models enabl=
ed by the Internet that are not necessarily scalable software companies. Ob=
viously independent publishing is one of these, and Stratechery is an examp=
le of the sort of business that is possible because of the Internet, even i=
f it is not the sort of tech company that I normally cover.

DNVR is another example in the Stratechery vein. I first met Adam Mares, th=
e co-founder of DNVR, last year, and within five minutes of talking with hi=
m I told him I would love to have him on for a Stratechery Interview. DNVR =
has created a new kind of publishing business that includes text, podcasts,=
 video, and, most surprisingly, an actual sports bar; I think it=E2=80=99s =
brilliant. And, given that the aforementioned NBA Finals include the Denver=
 Nuggets, this seemed like the perfect week to have Mares on.

This interview, though, is not about basketball (although we spend a couple=
 of minutes on it at the end): rather, it is an examination of a business t=
hat, if you step back, has started to recreate the geographic-driven differ=
entiation that undergirded the media businesses of old, but instead of bein=
g differentiated by owning printing presses and broadcast spectrum, DNVR di=
fferentiates itself with focus and community-building. To that end we get i=
nto Mares=E2=80=99 background and how DNVR came to be, why podcast advertis=
ing =E2=80=94 including gambling =E2=80=94 work so well for their model, an=
d whether it can be replicated in other cities.

